text:
PCi Security
Standards Council
Requirements and Testing Procedures
Guidance
3.6 Cryptographic keys used to protect stored account data are secured.
Defined Approach Requirements
Defined Approach Testing Procedures
3.6.1 Procedures are defined and implemented to
protect cryptographic keys used protect stored
account data against disclosure and misuse that
include:
Purpose
Cryptographic keys must be strongly protected
because those who obtain access will be able to
decrypt data.
3.6.1 Examine documented key-management
policies and procedures to verify that processes to
protect cryptographic keys used to protect stored
account data against disclosure and misuse are
defined to include all elements specified in this
requirement.
Good Practice
•
Access to keys is restricted to the fewest number
of custodians necessary.
Having a centralized key management system
based on industry standards is recommended for
managing cryptographic keys.
•
Further Information
Key-encrypting keys are at least as strong as the
data-encrypting keys they protect.
Key-encrypting keys are stored separately from
data-encrypting keys.
•
The entity's key management procedures will
benefit through alignment with industry
requirements, Sources for information on
cryptographic key management life cycles
include:
•
Keys are stored securely in the fewest possible
locations and forms.
•
Customized Approach Objective
ISO 11568-1 Banking - Key management
(retail) Part 1: Principles (specifically
Chapter 10 and the referenced Parts 2 & 4)
-
Processes that protect cryptographic keys used to
protect stored account data against disclosure and
misuse are defined and implemented.
NIST SP 800-57 Part 1 Revision 5
Recommendation for Key Management, Part
1: General.
Applicability Notes
This requirement applies to keys used to encrypt
stored account data and to key-encrypting keys
used to protect data-encrypting keys.
The requirement to protect keys used to protect
stored account data from disclosure and misuse
applies to both data-encrypting keys and key-
encrypting keys. Because one key-encrypting key
may grant access to many data-encrypting keys, the
key-encrypting keys require strong protection
measures.
